display="block"><![CDATA[         [X/G]_\bullet          = \big ((G^{\Delta _n}\times  X)/G\big )_{n\geqslant 0}.       \tag{6.1.2.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
      If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a principal homogeneous space for the group <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S=X/G]]></fr:tex>, then the map
      <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[         \begin {aligned}           G^{\Delta _n}\times  X           &\to  X^{\Delta _n}         \\(g_0,\ldots ,g_n,x)           &\mapsto  (g_0x,\ldots ,g_nx)         \end {aligned}       ]]></fr:tex>
      identifies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[X/G]_n]]></fr:tex> with the iterated fibre product <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(X/S)^{\Delta _n}]]></fr:tex>:
      <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {cosq}(X\to  S)         = ([X/G]_\bullet \to  S).       ]]></fr:tex>
      
      In particular, we have (by (III) of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5"
href="hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5.xml"
number="5.3.5" />)

      <fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2262</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.1.2.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[           \operatorname {H}^\bullet ([X/G]_\bullet )           \simeq  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X/G)         \tag{6.1.2.2}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

      (for a principal homogeneous space).
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
      For all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G^{\Delta _n}\times  X]]></fr:tex> is a principal homogeneous space for the group <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[X/G]_n]]></fr:tex>.
      For every equivariant sheaf <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {pr}_2^*F]]></fr:tex> is an equivariant sheaf on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G^{\Delta _n}\times  X]]></fr:tex>;
      by <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.1"
href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.1.xml"
number="6.1.1" />, the latter is the inverse image of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F^n]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[X/G]_n]]></fr:tex>.
      Every equivariant sheaf <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> thus defines a sheaf on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[X/G]_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
      It is easy to show that we thus obtain an equivalence between the category of equivariant sheaves on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> and the category of sheaves <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[X/G]_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> that satisfy

      <fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2264</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.1.star</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.star.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Property</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>*</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:em><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(*)]]></fr:tex> For every <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \Delta _n\to \Delta _m]]></fr:tex>, the structure morphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^*F^n\to  F^m]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism.</fr:em></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
      Construction (b) above is natural in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(G,X,F)]]></fr:tex>.
      We set

      <fr:tree
